							<h1>Culture </h1>
							<div class="to-animate col-md-11 col-sm-offset-1">			
								<p class="lead" align="Justify">A <b>Social Contract </b>that reflects Agile Values and is implemented across Agile teams strengthens Agile Culture. 
								It thus enables scaling of Agile practices. Social Contract evaluation should be part of the Project Retrospectives agenda and Client Steering Committee reviews.
								The purpose of a social contract is to document how a team wants to work together. It should balance inspirational statements with the details of actual behaviors and attitudes that the team want to see.
								A key advantage in having a social contract is that by defining what the team should look like, the team will start to consciously and unconsciously exhibit those behaviors and attitudes.
								<br/><br/>
								</p>
							</div>	
							<div class="to-animate col-md-10 col-sm-offset-1">
								<div class="panel panel-info">
									<div class="panel-heading text-center">A sample list of Social Contract points as agreed within a team - </div>
									<div class="panel-body col-sm-offset-1">
										<ol class="list-group text-left" >
											<li class="list-group-item-danger">All team members should join the Agile ceremonies on time.</li>
											<li class="list-group-item-info">Team should be dedicated to the current project.</li>
											<li class="list-group-item-warning">Don't dismiss other peoples opinion and try to understand their point of view.</li>
											<li class="list-group-item-danger">People should own the tasks and communicate effectively.</li>
											<li class="list-group-item-success">Ask for help.</li>
											<li class="list-group-item-success">Engage in more F2F and verbal communications rather than email chains.</li>
										</ol>
									</div>
								</div>
							</div>
